  ============================================================================
  PRE-TENANCY COMPLIANCE CHECKLIST (ENGLAND)

  Non-contractual guidance for landlords starting or transitioning a tenancy
  in England under the post-1 May 2026 regime.
  ============================================================================
--}}

{{#*inline "pre_tenancy_checklist_england"}}
<section class="checklist page-break-before" id="pre-tenancy-checklist">
  <div class="checklist-header">
    <h2>Pre-Tenancy Compliance Checklist</h2>
    <p class="checklist-jurisdiction">England</p>
  </div>

  <div class="checklist-disclaimer">
    <p><strong>NON-CONTRACTUAL GUIDANCE</strong></p>
    <p>This checklist is provided as guidance only and does not form part of the tenancy agreement. It summarises key landlord actions for the current England tenancy regime from 1 May 2026. For detailed requirements, consult the relevant legislation or seek professional legal advice.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>1. Deposit Protection (Mandatory)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Deposit protected within 30 days</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">If you take a deposit, you must protect it in a government-authorised scheme within 30 days of receiving it. Keep evidence of protection and prescribed information service.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Prescribed Information provided</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">You must provide the tenant with the scheme's prescribed information within 30 days. This includes scheme contact details, dispute resolution procedures, and the circumstances in which deductions may be claimed.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Housing Act 2004, ss.212-215 | The Housing (Tenancy Deposits) (Prescribed Information) Order 2007</p>

  <h3>2. Gas Safety (Mandatory if gas supplied)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Valid Gas Safety Certificate (CP12)</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">A Gas Safe registered engineer must inspect all gas appliances annually. The certificate must be provided to new tenants before they move in, and to existing tenants within 28 days of the check.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Copy provided to tenant before occupation</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">New tenants must receive a copy before the tenancy begins. Keep proof of provision.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Gas Safety (Installation and Use) Regulations 1998</p>

  <h3>3. Energy Performance Certificate (EPC)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Valid EPC with minimum E rating</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">The property must have an EPC rating of E or above. Properties rated F or G cannot be let unless a valid exemption is registered. The EPC must be valid.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>EPC provided to tenant</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Tenants must receive a copy of the EPC free of charge at the earliest opportunity.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Energy Performance of Buildings (England and Wales) Regulations 2012 | MEES Regulations 2015</p>

  <h3>4. Electrical Safety (EICR)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Electrical Installation Condition Report (EICR)</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">A qualified electrician must inspect the electrical installation every 5 years. The report must show the installation is satisfactory or any remedial work must be completed and evidenced.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Copy provided to tenant in time</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">New tenants must receive a copy before moving in. Existing tenants must receive a copy within the statutory period after inspection.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Electrical Safety Standards in the Private Rented Sector (England) Regulations 2020</p>

  <h3>5. England Written Information and Transition Duties</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>England written information prepared for this tenancy route</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">For a new England agreement, ensure the tenancy paperwork explains the tenant notice period, the Form 4A / Section 13 rent increase route, the landlord possession process, pets position, bills handling, and the core repair and safety duties that apply.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Proof of delivery retained for the written information you give</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Keep evidence such as an email receipt, signed acknowledgement, or dated handover note showing when the tenant received the written information.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Transition or information-sheet duty checked where applicable</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">{{#if (eq england_tenancy_purpose "existing_written_tenancy")}}For an existing written England tenancy, give the exact government Renters' Rights Act Information Sheet 2026 and keep proof of delivery.{{else if (eq england_tenancy_purpose "existing_verbal_tenancy")}}For an existing verbal England tenancy, give a written statement of the key terms together with the required England written information.{{else}}If this is a brand-new agreement, confirm the tenancy paperwork itself contains the required England written information for the current regime.{{/if}}</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Renters' Rights Act 2025 guidance | England written-information requirements from 1 May 2026</p>

  <h3>6. Rent in Advance, Bidding, and Discrimination</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Rent in advance handled lawfully</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Do not ask for, encourage, or accept rent before the tenancy agreement is signed. After signing, do not take more than 1 month's rent in advance for a new England assured tenancy.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Advertised rent and bidding rules followed</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">State a specific asking rent in writing and do not invite, encourage, or accept bids above that amount.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>No prohibited discrimination in letting decision</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Do not refuse or discourage the tenancy on an unlawful discriminatory basis, including because a household has children or receives benefits where the current law prohibits that conduct.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Renters' Rights Act 2025 guidance | England letting rules from 1 May 2026</p>

  <h3>7. Right to Rent Checks (Mandatory)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Right to Rent checks completed for all adult occupants</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Before the tenancy begins, verify that all adult occupants have the right to rent in England. Check original identity documents and keep copies for the duration of the tenancy plus 1 year.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Follow-up checks scheduled (if time-limited right)</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">If a tenant has a time-limited right to rent, schedule a follow-up check before their permission expires.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Immigration Act 2014 & 2016</p>

  <h3>8. Smoke and Carbon Monoxide Alarms</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Working smoke alarm on each storey</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">At least one working smoke alarm must be installed on each storey used as living accommodation. Test on the day the tenancy begins.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Carbon monoxide alarm in rooms with fixed combustion appliances</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">A carbon monoxide alarm is required in any room with a fixed combustion appliance (excluding gas cookers). This includes boilers, gas fires, wood burners, and oil heaters.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Alarms tested on day tenancy begins</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Confirm all alarms are in working order at the start of the tenancy and keep a record.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Smoke and Carbon Monoxide Alarm (Amendment) Regulations 2022</p>

  <h3>9. Landlord Contact Details</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Written notice of landlord's name and address provided</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Tenants must be informed in writing of the landlord's name and address and should also be given the practical service address stated for notices in the tenancy documents.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Landlord and Tenant Act 1985, s.1</p>

  <h3>10. HMO Requirements (If applicable)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>HMO licence obtained (if required)</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">If the property houses 5+ people from 2+ separate households sharing facilities, it requires a mandatory HMO licence. Some councils also require licensing for smaller HMOs - check with your local authority.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">â˜</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Fire safety measures in place</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">HMOs require additional fire safety measures such as compliant doors, alarms, lighting, and clear escape routes. Requirements vary by property size and local conditions.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Housing Act 2004 | The Licensing of Houses in Multiple Occupation (Mandatory Conditions of Licences) (England) Regulations 2018</p>

